rder and national salvation affected state-building and explores its lasting consequences. Glosser effectively argues that the replacement of the authoritarian, patriarchal, extended family structure with an egalitarian, conjugal family was a way for the nation to preserve crucial elements of its traditional culture. Her comprehensive research shows that in the end, family reform paved the way for the Chinese Communist Party to establish a deeply intrusive state that undermined the legitimacy of individual rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDomestic relationszChina. 0aFamilieszChinaxHistory. 0aFamily policyzChina. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  a20th century.  achina.  achinese culture.  achinese history.  acivil rights.  acommunist party.  aconjugal family.  aeconomic independence.  aegalitarian society.  afamily order.  afamily reform.  agovernment control.  ahuman rights.  aindividual rights.  amarriage choice.  amodern china.  anational salvation.  anationalism.  anew culture movement.  apatriarchy.  areform.  arepublican era.  asocial change.  asovereignty.  astate building.  asurveillance.  atotalitarianism.  aurban radicals.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022729340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092639440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520926394423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520926394/original  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  